menu "App LED PWM Configuration"

    menu "GPIO Configuration"
        help
            Configure the physical connection of the LED to the ESP32 chip.

        config APP_LED_PWM_GPIO_PIN
            int "GPIO Pin Number"
            range 1 100
            default 8
            help 
                The GPIO pin number that the LED is connected to.
                
                Important:
                - This pin will be configured as an output for the PWM signal.
                - Ensure the chosen pin is not used by any other peripheral
                  (e.g., UART, SPI, I2C) and is capable of PWM output.
                - On ESP32, pins 34-39 are input-only and cannot be used here.

        choice
            prompt "LED Active Level"
            default APP_LED_PWM_GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH
            help
                Determines what voltage level on the GPIO pin turns the LED on.
                
                This setting depends on your LED wiring:
                - If the LED's anode (long leg) is connected to the GPIO and
                  cathode (short leg) to GND, choose "Active High".
                - If the LED's cathode is connected to the GPIO and anode to VCC
                  (3.3V or 5V), choose "Active Low".
                
                The code will internally adjust the PWM duty cycle so that the
                brightness behavior is consistent regardless of your wiring.

            config APP_LED_PWM_GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW
                bool "Active Low (low voltage = LED on)"

            config APP_LED_PWM_GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH
                bool "Active High (high voltage = LED on)"

        endchoice
    endmenu

    menu "LEDC Configuration"
        help
            Configure the LEDC (LED PWM Controller) peripheral. The LEDC module
            generates the PWM signal that controls LED brightness.

        config APP_LED_PWM_LEDC_TIMER
            int "LEDC Timer No. (0-3)"
            range 0 3
            default 0
            help 
                Select which LEDC hardware timer to use. The ESP32 has 4 timers
                (0 to 3). Each timer can drive multiple channels at the same
                frequency but with independent duty cycles.
                
                If you plan to use other PWM outputs in your project, choose a
                timer that is not already in use.

        config APP_LED_PWM_LEDC_CHANNEL
            int "LEDC Channel No. (0-7)"
            range 0 7
            default 0
            help 
                Select which LEDC channel to use. The ESP32 provides 8 channels
                (0-7) that can be bound to any timer. The channel determines
                which GPIO will output the PWM signal (set separately).
                
                Again, avoid channels already used by other parts of your code.

        config APP_LED_PWM_LEDC_PWM_FREQUENCY
            int "PWM Frequency (Hz)"
            default 5000
            help 
                The frequency of the PWM signal in Hertz.
                
                For LED brightness control, a frequency above ~100 Hz is
                recommended to avoid visible flicker. Common values are:
                - 500 Hz   : Very stable, works everywhere.
                - 5000 Hz  : Smooth dimming, quiet (avoids audible noise).
                - 20000 Hz : High frequency, often used with camera.
                
                Note: The achievable frequency depends on the duty resolution
                (see resolution setting below). If you request a frequency that
                is too high for the chosen resolution, initialization will fail.

        # ========== 分辨率设置方式选择 ==========
        choice
            prompt "Duty Resolution Setting Mode"
            default APP_LED_PWM_DUTY_RES_AUTO
            help
                Choose how the duty resolution (number of discrete brightness
                steps) is determined.
                
                Duty resolution defines the granularity of brightness control.
                For example, 8-bit resolution gives 256 brightness levels,
                13-bit gives 8192 levels.
                
                Higher resolution gives smoother fading but reduces the maximum
                possible PWM frequency because the internal counter takes more
                clock cycles to complete one PWM period.
                
                Relationship formula:
                    Max Frequency = Source Clock (usually 80 MHz) / (2^Resolution)
                
                Two modes are available:
                
                [Auto Mode]
                The driver automatically selects the highest resolution that can
                still achieve your configured PWM frequency. This is the safest
                option and recommended for beginners.
                
                [Manual Mode]
                You specify the exact resolution in bits. This gives you full
                control, but you must ensure that the combination of frequency
                and resolution is valid. The code will check this and report an
                error if impossible.

            config APP_LED_PWM_DUTY_RES_AUTO
                bool "Auto (calculate from frequency)"

            config APP_LED_PWM_DUTY_RES_MANUAL
                bool "Manual (specify resolution)"

        endchoice

        config APP_LED_PWM_LEDC_DUTY_RESOLUTION
            int "Duty Resolution (bits)"
            range 1 20
            default 13
            depends on APP_LED_PWM_DUTY_RES_MANUAL
            help
                (Only available when Manual mode is selected above.)
                
                Set the duty resolution in bits. The number of brightness steps
                will be 2^Resolution.
                
                Examples:
                - 8 bits  : 256 steps, max frequency ~312.5 kHz (with 80 MHz clock)
                - 10 bits : 1024 steps, max frequency ~78 kHz
                - 12 bits : 4096 steps, max frequency ~19.5 kHz
                - 13 bits : 8192 steps, max frequency ~9.77 kHz
                - 14 bits : 16384 steps, max frequency ~4.88 kHz
                - 16 bits : 65536 steps, max frequency ~1.22 kHz
                
                Make sure your configured PWM frequency (APP_LED_PWM_LEDC_PWM_FREQUENCY)
                is less than or equal to the maximum frequency for the chosen
                resolution. If not, the application will fail with an error
                message during initialization.
                
                The ESP32 LEDC hardware supports up to 20 bits, but very high
                resolutions severely limit the frequency. For LED fading, 10-14
                bits are usually sufficient.

        config APP_LED_PWM_LEDC_FADE_TIME
            int "LED Fade Time (milliseconds)"
            default 1500
            help 
                Duration of a complete fade-in or fade-out transition, in
                milliseconds.
                
                This time is used both for fading from off to full brightness
                and from full brightness to off. A larger value creates a
                slower, smoother breathing effect; a smaller value makes the
                transition quicker.
                
                Typical values: 1000 - 3000 ms for a gentle breathing LED.
            
    endmenu

endmenu